05388nam a22008175i 9789048532582DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485325827 a10.1515/97890485325822doi  a(DE-B1597)550721  a(OCoLC)1191863643  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0100002bisacsh1 aSpaans, Ronny, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDangerous Drugs :bThe Self-Presentation of the Merchant-Poet Joannes Six van Chandelier (1620-1695) /cRonny Spaans. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (456 p.) :b3 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmsterdam Studies in the Dutch Golden Age00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tPart I. Introduction -- t1. Theory and reception -- tPart II. Medicinal and Sacred Drugs -- t2. The sober druggist -- t3. Drugs in the Wunderkammer -- t4. Drugs as remedies -- t5. Drugs as material and linguistic cosmetics -- t6. Drugs as explosives -- t7. Drugs as Sacred Offerings -- t8. Drugs as intoxicants -- tPart III. Divine Blood for Sale -- t9. The human body as a drug -- t10. Conclusion -- tAppendix I: 'Rariteiten te koop' -- tAppendix II: Family and business network of Joannes Six van Chandelier -- tBibliography -- tGeneral index -- tIndex of poems0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 17th century, the Dutch Republic was the centre of the world trade in exotic drugs and spices. They were sought after both as medicines, and as luxury objects for the bourgeois class, giving rise to a medical and moral anxiety in the Republic.[-]This ambivalent view on exotic drugs is the theme of the poetry of Joannes Six van Chandelier (1620-1695). Six, who himself ran the drug shop 'The Gilded Unicorn' in Amsterdam, addresses a number of exotic medicines in his poems, such as musk, incense, the miracle drug theriac, Egyptian mumia, and even the blood of Charles I of England.[-]In Dangerous Drugs, these texts are studied for the first time. The study shows how Six, through a process of self-presentation as a sober and restrained merchant, but also as a penitent sinner, thirsting for God's grace, links early modern drug abuse to different desires, such as lust, avarice, pride and curiosity. The book shows also how an early modern debate on exotic drugs contributed to an important shift in early modern natural science, from a drug lore based on mythical and fabulous concepts, to a botany based on observation and systematic examination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aEarly Modern Period. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary History and Criticism. 4aMedicine. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aDrugs, exotics, poetry, golden age, calvinism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048532582zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048532582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/